   06-13-2012 10:00 PM - edited 06-13-2012 10:02 PM

   G'day all


   I'm T2 so I don't get over here often. However, as I am a Rugby League
   fan I thought some of you may be interested in seeing one of our local
   players.


   I won't even try to explain the rules of Rugby League to Americans.
   Sufficient to mention some of the differences between American football
   and Rugby league.


   The game only stops twice, at half-time and full time. There are no
   time outs although the game may be stopped by the referee temporarily
   for injured players to be treated, but only if where they are lying
   interferes with play. The coach can replace any of the 13 on-field
   players from four reserves during the match, but only up to ten times.
   Thus the Offence and Defence are the same team. No helmets and limited
   padding.The ball can only be passed back, not forwards. A touchdown is
   called a "try" and the ball must actually be touched down to score.


   The Australian NRL is roughly equivalent to NFL or AFL. Instead of a
   Superbowl system we have "Origin" which is where the best players from
   the two major Rugby League states play three times each year. Players
   are selected based on their state of origin; a bit like your all-pro
   teams. These are considered the toughest and roughest games in Rugby
   League.


   An edited version of last night's "Origin II" match is on the link
   below. One of the stars was Brett Stewart, who plays full-back for New
   South Wales, number 1 in the blue uniforms. He appears in sequences
   commencing at 0:20 and 2:55.


   Brett is a type 1.


   [53]State of Origin II: As it happened
   Cheers, Alan, Type 2, d&e metformin 2000mg, Australia.
     __________________________________________________________________

   Everything in Moderation - Except Laughter.
   There is nothing I could eat I like more than my eyes.
